\section{Common \code{mellio_open()} inputs}{

\code{mellio_open()} supports common \code{htest} objects such as \code{t.test()},
\code{cor.test()}, and \code{chisq.test()}; model objects such as \code{lm}, \code{glm},
\code{aov}, \code{lme4} mixed models, \code{lavaan} fits, survival models, ordinal
models, and selected optional-package result classes; data frames,
matrices, and base \code{table} objects; \code{ggplot2}, lattice, htmlwidget,
recorded plot, and image-file inputs.
}

\section{Common \code{melliotab()} workflow}{

Use \code{melliotab(x)} to create a table, then apply table modifiers such as
\code{mt_title()}, \code{mt_note()}, \code{mt_decimals()}, \code{mt_format_ci()},
\code{mt_sig_stars()}, \code{mt_spanner()}, \code{mt_section_title()}, and
\code{mt_simplify_headers()}. Pass two or more model objects to
\code{melliotab(m1, m2, ...)} to create a side-by-side model comparison table.
For file-based handoff, use \code{mt_copy()} or \code{mt_save()} to copy or save a
finished table as HTML, LaTeX, or Markdown.
}

